videoTitle: Air Force Recruitment
commentText: In the early 80s, I tried to go Air Force, first.  It was October 1982, and my girlfriend/wife was pregnant & due in May of 1983.  I would have accepted ANY job/MOS from the Air Force, as long as they had me active duty prior to May 1983. The ONLY job they offered me, was SP (security police,) with a 10-month delayed entry (Aug 1983.) I tested VERY WELL = Cateegory A, white male. I took my packet to the Army recruiter.  They printed out a six-foot long list of jobs/MOSs that I was qualified for.  Among them, were journalist and broadcast journslist.  I signed-up to become an Army Journslist, and it was one of the BEST decisions of my life!!!  Plus, they got me into active duty by Feb. 1983 (three months before the baby was due.) I was willing to he a fry cook, or infantry -- WHATEVER!!! So long as I was active duty before May 1983.  Note:  The Defense Information School (DINFOS) is a joint-service program.  Thus, I was training side-by-side with not just Army journslism candidates, but ALSO those from the Air Force, Navy, Coast Guard and Marine Corps. Note:  All military branches pay THE SAME!!!!  I entered the Army as an E2, then promoted to E3 during journalism training, then promoted to E4 shortly after arriving at my permanent-party location. Bottom line:  Air Force has tunnel-vision.  Your options are limited.  Army is the biggest/largest organization, and they can offer you DOZENS/HUNDRENDS more opportunities than the USAF.

videoTitle: Air Force Recruitment
commentText: Should have sent him to corp of engineers. It's kinda a shame you gotta enlist for the military and your test scores determine your service path. It used to be the military would take young men with no skills lacking direction and purpose in life and train and educate them so that they become proficient, professional, specialists in whatever they were determined to achieve. One of my friends in HS was doing the same as everyone else I grew up with. He's a kid of immigrants, they were dirt poor. We were all droppin acid and x, carrying guns, hanging with bad crowd making poor choices. His cousin fronted him Like 5 lbs of weed and he ended up only coming up with enough $ for two. So he enlisted in the Navy at 17. 'm going on a limb and assuming the enlistment bonus has some influence motivating the decision.   But 25 years later he's literally a model of the American dream. He worked hard and studied, got into a submarine after training to beq missle specialist/tech (don't ask me how he got the clearance, it blows mind to think people who grew up like  we did are entrusted with the worlds most powerful weapons arsenal)   But moral of the story is he's is a American success story. The Navy took a troubled youth, gave him an opportunity, nd he worked his ass off and had a rewarding career proudly serving his country and set himself up to be able to live a life of prosperity that he can be proud of providing a life and comforts for his family that he couldn't imagine when he was growing up.   I think the military is limiting some of the best talent by requirements to pass tests and bein skilled before starting a career path. Like this guy already was a welder. All he was looking for was the opportunity to learn and turn knowing how to weld into something that served the country and taught him skills and assets to become something greater. commentText: As a technical writer who's performed in both the User Manual Writer and the Documentation Writer spaces for 35 years or so, a few words of advice:  *_1  If you're going to be hired for your writing skills, you'd better have some._*  I've known a lot of 'technical writers' that struggled to deliver a product at a 6th grade level, while most corporate or government technical writing is going to be at 12th grade level or up.  *_2  Don't expect AI to save you._*  Technical writing is typically very narrow in scope and since the content will likely be new, any LLM-trained AI is not going to be able to write your content for you.  *_3  In addition to crafting prose in the King's English, you'll also need familiarity with HTML, SGML, and XML._*  Familiarity with different graphics formats, and their advantages/disadvantages, is a MUST.  *_4  Lastly, as a technical writer, you're going to need technical background beyond being able to record a macro in Microsoft Word._*  I spent 22 years as a Navy Electronics Tech with over 8000 hours of technical training.  That was a good start.

commentText: I once got fired from my dishwasher job for trying to call off sick. Was working there for over a year, and it was my 1st time calling out. I even had a doctor's note that I was contagious, and not to work around food.  Edit- I've been getting a lot of people questioning if this was true, and it absolutely is. I agree, doesn't make sense at all to fire someone you've been praising for over a year as your best dish washer, and is currently your only dishwasher after the other guy retired, just for calling out for the very first time with a 103 degree fever and a doctor's note.  No, it's not illegal per se, because I live in a no fault state, but I did speak to a lawyer. He assured me I had a case, and that it was a guaranteed victory, but since I'd only just recently become full time, I hadn't made enough for the settlement to have been worth the lawyer fees. Even in no fault states, you can still sue if you're fired for discriminatory purposes, like being black, gay or sick. That's how these companies get away with it, because they know people aren't likely to spend thousands of dollars just to say they were right.

commentText: In New Zealand, there is a dismissal process and a good reason must be given, otherwise the employer can be sued. Also, appropriate notice must be given, unless it's a case of serious misconduct. In any circumstance, the person losing their job is still entitled to any annual holidays etc. they are owed, in their final pay. Here, healthcare is not tied to your job either, as most medical things are covered by the government anyway, except about $60 for GP visits. If you're fired, you can get the job seekers allowance almost immediately, plus accommodation supplement to get you through. commentText: I was let go at a job about 10 months ago.   I was supposed to give them 30 days notice, I was given notice the day they came in and told me.   Depending on which state you live in unemployment is not a given.   It took me 9 months to find another job.   Luckily I had some savings.   I did not get healthy insurance (Medicaid) until after 6 months of being unemployed.   It was a tedious process that took forever.   I was afraid to drive my car anywhere because of lack of insurance.   I had to get food from a food bank because my 20 year old son could not get a job.   So I was buying groceries for him.   I was also paying for his college tuition.    It was a hard and difficult time.   Oh and the job I did end up taking is only 1099 (contracted) work.  I had to take it.   The only salary position that would potentially be available to me would not have started until almost a year after my last job.   The U.S. needs better labor protections.

videoTitle: JOB HUNTING IN JAPAN IS ACTUAL PAIN
commentText: For fresh grads, Japanese companies traditionally want the stereotypical genki person who shows they are eager to absorb the company philosophy and be whatever the company wants to mold them to be. Actual degree and skills don't really matter. This is how you end up with new hires at IT companies who have no IT background whatsoever spending their first 6 months at company training learning how to code in Java.

videoTitle: JOB HUNTING IN JAPAN IS ACTUAL PAIN
commentText: A major Japanese company that has announced that they've switched to English as company-wide language, during the interview, once I've competed numerous other stages: oh, you only speak basic Japanese? We only say English is our company language, it's actually Japanese. Another rejection was from a foreign company in Tokyo. It was the last stage and I was about to get hired. As a final question I asked what the work-life-balance was like. The whole room just shifted and they offered me an internship trial period instead. Funny that they don't realize it's not only them picking an employee but also an employee picking an employer..

videoTitle: JOB HUNTING IN JAPAN IS ACTUAL PAIN
commentText: I got to the interview stage only to be told "yeah, we already filled your role with a Japanese guy" ğŸ¤ª FML If you really want a job in Japan as a foreigner, I think it's a *must* to apply through a hiring agency. DO NOT APPLY DIRECTLY TO COMPANIES. First off, expectations of what a CV is are very different in Japan. If your CV stands out, they won't even look at it. Your CV has to follow a very specific format and list very specific details about your previous jobs.  My hiring agency coached me through the CV making process and even gave me mock interviews in Japanese with feedback on how to improve my "Japan-ness". I got loads of interviews and multiple offers thanks to them. Finally, be aware that you're more likely to get hired in spring rather than autumn. Fresh graduates begin job hunting in March/April and many employers don't account for hiring outside of that window unless it's an emergency.

videoTitle: JOB HUNTING IN JAPAN IS ACTUAL PAIN
commentText: I've spent the last 10 years working for a Japanese company in Asia. There's so many issues with Japanese business culture in the modern world that they don't want to address. 1. Managers from the 1990s who don't even know how to use a computer are still running the show. This is the equivalent of a war general from the late 1800s running the military campaign in ww2. 2. They fill the day with so many pointless activities that staff can be spending 50% of their day writing up processes on why you should make sure your shoes are tied up so you don't fall over or a 7 hour meeting on if water should be allowed on desks, so that no one ever has time to develop at their actual job. 3. They put loyalty over salary. Meanwhile, Chinese and western companies are offering 2-3x the salaries and poaching all their good staff. 4. Everything is compartmentalized within departments/divisions and those groups have to have targets. So there's groups constantly setting the same targets, not telling the other groups and then both groups failing when the other groups won't collaborate with them on their project because they're too busy working on their own project with the same goal but a different methodology to achieve it. 5. The culture makes you feel difficult for questioning anything with management.  Younger Japanese are aware of these issues. But given the opportunity to move into management, a lot of them will tow the line and join the club of inefficiency in order to maintain power and the better pay. So I don't see it changing in the future either. It's like a self perpetuating system of pure inefficiency. And they're self aware that the Chinese companies will destroy them. But they can't change their culture to survive. Its like Japanese people saw a Panda in the mid 90s and said "yeah, that's how we should do things too".

commentText: Something similar happened to me, but it was on an international airport in Munich. I was 19 years old and on our way to visit family in China, and when we were about to walk through the EU customs ATM, a white dude asked us where we got our Austrian passport. I've been flying to China and back to Austria, since I moved to Austria in 2002. We got our citizenship in 2003 and until then, no one questioned our citizenship! When I walked through customs, and I told him that we got our citizenship from the government, he didn't believe me. Well, I told him that I don't care what he thinks, and if the passport would be fake I wouldn't be standing on the other side of the ATM. That made his grin fall and got the hell out of there. If he would've kept bothering us, I would've asked for the police. Assholes are everywhere.

commentText: The best-kept secret of nailing a job interview is "LIKEABILITY." Human beings make decisions based on emotions and justify them with logic afterwards. If the interviewer doesn't like you, your experiences and credentials are irrelevant.  Remember, if you land the job, you and the interviewer will be bumping into each other every day at work and potentially working on the same projects. Keep in mind that interviewers research you online, including LinkedIn and social media (be mindful of what you post online); they often prejudge you based on your social media presence or photos.

videoTitle: The BEST Questions To Ask In Job Interviews
commentText: I do  things differently.  I have two questions for you.  First what is the reason you like to work here. Listen to what they tell you. It is a personal question. If they just regurgitate standard company blabla I look for signs of them feeling uncomfortable. Mayor red flag.  Second: What do you think the people in the position of the job you are hiring for value most?  I want insight about the company culture.  Of course if they want me, they will tailor the second answer bit to what they expect I like.   Generally spoken, recommended questions for job interviews have a short shelf life, HR adopts fast.

commentText: I think a big part of why itâ€™s not being talked about, is because a lot of people donâ€™t see it as any different than the longstanding [it was already being parodied in _Office Space_ (1999) ] corporate trend of dumping employees in favor of contractors with no benefits. So this was already a huge problem, and the inclusion of foreign contractors in countries with significantly lower costs of living changes it, but doesnâ€™t _dramatically_ change it. Itâ€™s an acceleration, not an inflection point.   Which doesnâ€™t mean that itâ€™s not bad or not worth talking about. And the acceleration can make a thing that was a minor problem around the edges into a society-undermining problem. But most humans are very bad at recognizing creeping threats, very bad at planning for nebulous threats, and bad-to-very-bad at cognitive empathy. So I think the lack of conversation reflects lack of recognizing that this is a systemic problem. Thanks for bringing it up!  But I also think this reflects factionalism and lack of much trans-national worker solidarity to counterbalance the power of transnational corporations. In the US, big transnational corporations and some politicians have for 50+ years mostly succeeded in scapegoating workers in lower-COL countries and pitting US workers against them. Most of the US unions completely fell for this in the 1970s-1990s, pushing to prevent offshoring of manufacturing jobs through contracts and legislation, instead of pushing to unionize the foreign workers. They saw foreign workers as unfair  competition instead of recognizing the corporations and shareholders as the source of the problem.
